<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-401-308  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 401 308.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  April 30 1990 n465 p19(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hospitals struggle to integrate.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wallach, Rachel Meltzer.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Short-term, acute care community hospitals face problems inintegrating their disparate information systems because of yearsof piecemeal buying and decentralized and uncoordinated units.andO;The demands of hospitals for integration and the inability ofvendors to easily meet that demand puts a strain on customerrelations.andP;  Strategic planning by hospital executives is neededfor continued automation and for networking existing systems.andO;These plans must be developed at a time of when hospital costs arerising and budgets for computer information systems are declining.andO;Companies in most other industries spend about four to fivepercent of their budgets on computer automation but hospitals onlyspent 2.2 percent in 1989.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Hospital Information SystemsComputer Systems IntegrationMISConnectivityStrategic PlanningCustomer Relations.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Decreasing health care automation spending. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>